To crowdsource Figure 5A and B: first perform clustering on the TCGA dataset; then group GDSC cell lines according to the TCGA clustering results; after grouping, compare drug sensitivity between groups using AUC for quantitative analysis.

https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6694/13/9/2128 Fromhttps://www.mdpi.com/2072-6694/13/9/2128

Figure 5. Drug discovery and immune characterization in essential gene-classified clusters of lung adenocarcinoma (LUAD). (A) Heatmap showing essential gene-stratified-clusters exhibiting distinct expressions in GDSC lung cancer cells. (B) Drug response area under the receiver operator characteristics curve (AUC) of SN-38 and talazoparib within essential geneclassified clusters demonstrated as a boxplot.

To identify drugs that exhibited distinct efficacy in essential gene-classified clusters, the prediction model was applied to the GDSC database (Figure 5A). Areas under the receiver operator characteristics curve (AUC) of drug responses within clusters were compared. Totally, the GDSC database contains 367 compounds. Only 257 compounds which were tested on more than 75% of the LUAD cell lines were used for analyses (Tables S8 and S9). AUCs of SN-38, a topoisomerase I inhibitor, and talazoparib, a poly(ADP ribose) polymerase (PARP) inhibitor, were significantly lower in cluster 1 LUAD cells (Figure 5B). This suggested that cluster 1 tumors with highly proliferative signatures were vulnerable to drugs targeting DNA-replication mechanisms.

FigureYa240CRISPRFigureYa240CRISPRCRISPR screening31TCGATCGAvs This is the same paper as FigureYa240CRISPR. FigureYa240CRISPR used a CRISPR screening database to find 31 genes essential for lung cancer cell survival, extrapolated to the TCGA database, and found these genes were indeed significantly different between TCGA cancer vs.normal.

Whats the significance? Can it guide clinical practice?

TCGAGDSC This time, subtypes derived from the TCGA expression profile are extrapolated to GDSC cell lines, thereby inferring drug sensitivity for each subtype.

Custom function

standarize.fun <- function(indata=NULL, halfwidth=NULL, centerFlag=T, scaleFlag=T) {
  outdata=t(scale(t(indata), center=centerFlag, scale=scaleFlag))
  if (!is.null(halfwidth)) {
    outdata[outdata>halfwidth]=halfwidth
    outdata[outdata<(-halfwidth)]= -halfwidth
  }
  return(outdata)
}

luad.expr <- fread("TCGA-LUAD.htseq_fpkm.tsv.gz",sep = "\t",check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T,data.table = F)
rownames(luad.expr) <- luad.expr$Ensembl_ID; 
luad.expr <- luad.expr[,setdiff(colnames(luad.expr),"Ensembl_ID")]
Ginfo <- read.delim("gencode.v22.annotation.gene.probeMap",sep = "\t",row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T)

comgene <- intersect(rownames(luad.expr),rownames(Ginfo)) # 
# Intersect genes between expression and gene annotation
luad.expr <- luad.expr[comgene,]
Ginfo <- Ginfo[comgene,]
luad.expr$gene <- Ginfo$gene
luad.expr <- luad.expr[!duplicated(luad.expr$gene),]; rownames(luad.expr) <- luad.expr$gene; luad.expr <- luad.expr[,setdiff(colnames(luad.expr),"gene")] # 
# Remove duplicates by gene symbol

tumsam <- colnames(luad.expr)[substr(colnames(luad.expr),14,16) == "01A"] # TCGA-LUAD

TCGA - TCGA Data Typing - Unsupervised Consensus Clustering

36essential genesFigureYa240CRISPRTCGApatientconsensus clustering3 Using the 36 essential genes defined in the original paper (see FigureYa240CRISPR for the selection method), perform unsupervised consensus clustering on TCGA patients into 3 subtypes, then plot a heatmap to visualize.

#  | set colors
red <- "#E53837"
blue <- "#6AADF0"
yellow <- "#F7A400"
heatmap.BLYW <- c("#3F047D","white","#B05900")

genes <- c("NUF2","GINS1","TOP2A","CDC6","NDC80","RRM2",
           "CCNA2","KIF11","PRC1","BUB1B","CDCA8","TPX2",
           "PLK1","CDC45","CDC20","BIRC5","ECT2","PCNA",
           "CHAF1B","TIMELESS","GINS2","ORC6","CDT1","MCM2",
           "MCM4","RCC1","BOP1","ALDOA","PSMG3","DKC1",
           "HSPD1","BYSL","RPP40","SNRPE","HSPE1","CCT3")

indata <- luad.expr[genes,tumsam]
cc <- ConsensusClusterPlus(d = as.matrix(indata),
                           maxK = 3, # 3 | maximum K=3
                           reps = 1000, # 1000 | 1000 permutations
                           pItem = 0.95, # 95% | 95% resampling of genes each iteration
                           clusterAlg = "pam", # PAM | use PAM
                           seed = 19991018,
                           title = ".",
                           plot = "pdf")
## end fraction
## clustered
## clustered
group <- paste0("Cluster",cc[[3]]$consensusClass); names(group) <- tumsam #  | retrieve 3-cluster labels
group <- sort(group) #  | sort by cluster

Draw a heatmap to inspect subtype separation

plotdata <- standarize.fun(indata[,names(group)],halfwidth = 2) # z-score2 | z-score and cap at |2|

annCol.tcga <- data.frame(Cluster = as.character(group), #  | build sample annotation
                          row.names = names(group),
                          stringsAsFactors = F)
annColors <- list("Cluster" = c("Cluster1" = red,"Cluster2" = yellow,"Cluster3" = blue)) #  | annotation colors

#  | draw heatmap
pheatmap(plotdata,
         color = NMF:::ccRamp(x = heatmap.BLYW,n=64) , #  | color scheme as in paper
         annotation_col = annCol.tcga[colnames(plotdata),,drop = F],
         annotation_colors = annColors,
         cluster_cols = FALSE, #  | keep TCGA columns ordered by subtype
         cluster_rows = TRUE, #  | cluster rows
         border_color = NA,
         treeheight_row = 20, #  | row dendrogram height
         cellheight = 10, #  | cell height
         cellwidth = 0.6, #  | cell width
         show_rownames = TRUE, #  | show rownames
         show_colnames = FALSE, #  | hide colnames
         filename = "heatmap of essential genes in tcga luad.pdf")

rownames(gdsc.auc) <- gdsc.auc$ARXSPAN_ID; gdsc.auc <- gdsc.auc[,-1]
colnames(gdsc.auc) <- gsub("AUC_PUBLISHED.","",colnames(gdsc.auc),fixed = T) # AUC | matrix rows=cell lines, cols=drugs

comdep <- intersect(rownames(gdsc.auc),ccle.anno$depMapID) # LUAD | LUAD lines with drug data
gdsc.auc <- gdsc.auc[comdep,]
rmdrug <- colnames(gdsc.auc)[apply(gdsc.auc,2, function(x) {sum(is.na(x)) > 0.10 * length(comdep)})] # 10%25% | remove drugs missing in >10% lines (paper used 25%)
gdsc.auc <- gdsc.auc[,setdiff(colnames(gdsc.auc),rmdrug)]  #  | drop these drugs
gdsc.auc <- as.data.frame(impute.knn(t(gdsc.auc))$data) # KNN | KNN-impute remaining missing

index <- match(colnames(gdsc.auc),ccle.anno$depMapID) # DepmapID | match DepMap IDs to line names
colnames(gdsc.auc) <- rownames(ccle.anno)[index] # DepmapID | replace with line names

##  | read cell line expression
ccle.expr <- fread("CCLE_RNAseq_rsem_genes_tpm_20180929.txt.gz",sep = "\t",check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F,header = T,data.table = F)
rownames(ccle.expr) <- ccle.expr$gene_id
ccle.expr <- ccle.expr[,-c(1:2)]; rownames(ccle.expr) <- sapply(strsplit(rownames(ccle.expr),".",fixed = T),"[",1) # ENSEMBL ID | harmonize Ensembl IDs
Ginfo2 <- Ginfo; rownames(Ginfo2) <- sapply(strsplit(rownames(Ginfo2),".",fixed = T), "[",1)
comgene <- intersect(rownames(ccle.expr),rownames(Ginfo2))
ccle.expr <- ccle.expr[comgene,]
Ginfo2 <- Ginfo2[comgene,]
ccle.expr$gene <- Ginfo2$gene
ccle.expr <- ccle.expr[!duplicated(ccle.expr$gene),]; rownames(ccle.expr) <- ccle.expr$gene; ccle.expr <- ccle.expr[,setdiff(colnames(ccle.expr),"gene")] #  | remove duplicates by gene symbol

## LUAD | select LUAD lines with both drug and expression
comccle <- intersect(intersect(rownames(ccle.anno),colnames(ccle.expr)),colnames(gdsc.auc)) # LUAD | intersection across meta/expression/drug
comgene <- intersect(genes,rownames(ccle.expr))
ccle.expr <- log2(ccle.expr[comgene,comccle] + 1) #  | log2-transform expression
ccle.anno <- ccle.anno[comccle,]

nearest centroid classifier

Build nearest centroid classifier and assign cell line subtypes

nearest centroid classifierclassifierGDSCTCGA nearest centroid classifierclassifierGDSCTCGA Build a nearest centroid classifier from TCGA and use it to predict GDSC cell lines, assigning them to the three TCGA-derived groups.

z-score The original paper used centering to build the classifier; results here were suboptimal, so z-score standardization was used instead.

indata <- t(scale(t(luad.expr[comgene,names(group)]))) #z-score | z-score standardization

# nearest centroid classifier | build nearest centroid classifier
classifier <- lol.classify.nearestCentroid(t(indata), as.numeric(factor(group))) 

#testdata <- sweep(ccle.expr[comgene,], 1, apply(ccle.expr[comgene,], 1, median))
testdata <- t(scale(t(ccle.expr))) # z-score | z-score the test set

# classifier | apply classifier to cell lines
ccle.group <- paste0("Cluster",predict(classifier, t(testdata))); names(ccle.group) <- colnames(testdata) 
ccle.group <- sort(ccle.group) #  | sort predicted labels

Kruskal Kruskal-Wallis test for drug sensitivity

GDSC Compute sensitivity per subtype for each drug, output stats, and plot.

GDSCTCGA Sensitivity patterns in GDSC-assigned subtypes can be extrapolated back to TCGA subtypes.

outTab <- NULL
for(drug in rownames(gdsc.auc)) {
  tmp <- data.frame(auc = as.numeric(gdsc.auc[drug,names(ccle.group)]),
                    group = as.character(ccle.group))
  avg <- with(tmp, tapply(auc, group, mean)) # AUC | mean AUC per subtype
  kt <- kruskal.test(auc~group, data = tmp) # kruskal | Kruskal-Wallis test
  outTab <- rbind.data.frame(outTab,
                             data.frame(drug = drug,
                                        avg1 = avg[1],
                                        avg2 = avg[2],
                                        avg3 = avg[3],
                                        pvalue = kt$p.value,
                                        stringsAsFactors = F),
                             stringsAsFactors = F)

  if(kt$p.value < 0.05) {
    message(drug," pass statistical significance...")

    #  | plot boxplot for significant drugs
    p <- ggplot(tmp, aes(group, auc, fill=group)) +
      geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA) +
      geom_point(shape = 21, size=2,
                 position = position_jitterdodge(),
                 aes(color=group), alpha = 0.6) +
      scale_fill_manual(values = c(red,yellow,blue)) +
      scale_color_manual(values = c(red,yellow,blue)) +
      xlab(NULL) + ylab(paste0("AUC of ", drug)) +
      theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
            axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10, color = "black"),
            axis.ticks.x = element_blank(),
            panel.background = element_blank(),
            panel.grid = element_blank(),
            legend.position = "right",
            legend.title = element_blank()) +
      stat_compare_means(method = "kruskal.test", 
                         label.y = 0.98) # AIPDF | adjust label position as needed or later in a vector editor
    ggsave(filename = paste0("boxplot of estimated auc in ",drug,".pdf"), 
           width = 4,height = 3.5)
  }
}
